diff:1189517146:1189516175:=5,52c5,44%0a%3c Before you start pillaging and burning you must learn somethings about%0a%3c your weapons and it's usage.%0a%3c %0a%3c Ship Roles: Not all ships are made equal%0a%3c ========================================%0a%3c %0a%3c One of the problems with balanced fleet doctrine is that it tends to%0a%3c make people think they need to use ships that they have no need for in a%0a%3c fleet, giving their enemies an opportunity to destroy them more%0a%3c efficiently. Balance is good, yes, but that does mean you should be%0a%3c building frigates and including them in your fleets to disperse the%0a%3c damage. Let's take a look at all of your units and their applications.%0a%3c While some units are better than others, most have something they do%0a%3c well.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c :Fighters: These are the staple of all fleets in AE---defense, offense, everything. Fighters are the single most efficient ship in the game. The damage they absorb per credit is unparalleled. That makes fighters your #1 unit for use as cannon fodder. When we say you can never have too many fighters, we're being quite literal. A fleet that runs out of fighters will take far higher losses, and can be defeated in detail for obscene exchange rates by anyone who manages to catch them. Build thousands for base defense, and then keep building them for use with offensive fleets. You go through fighters at an obscene rate because fighters are basically designed to die. Application of fighter waves in combat can totally change your exchange rate for the better.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Bombers: Same armor as fighters with twice the firepower and twice the cost. These are less efficient, but still make for pretty efficient meat. Their ability to harm cruisers makes them especially handy. Don't go overboard with Bombers, but they make a good addition to any fleet that needs to absorb a lot of damage, or one that's hitting a large group of cruisers. Since most people use a lot of cruisers, bombers can be very useful.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Heavy Bombers (HBs): Heavy Bombers pack enough punch to take out main fleet units---Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers---but they're vulnerable and expensive, as well. Heavy Bombers are best used in waves after you have used fighter waves to destroy the enemy's unshielded units. Heavy Bombers are inefficient against unshielded units, and therefore should not be used in main fleet engagements. Enemy fighters will cut them to ribbons. HBs are also the best ships for breaking occupations if you have a proper amount of Command Centers.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Ion Bombers (IBs): Double the price of Heavy Bombers, with the same power and armor. All they gain is one point of shielding, which does practically nothing for their survivability, and their weapons become Ion based, so 50%25 penetrates shielding. Oh, yay. These things suck. They're so expensive that they're not even efficient in waves. If you send a wave of Ion Bombers against capital ships of equal value---be they cruisers, HCs, or BBs---it's impossible for the Ion Bombers to come out ahead in the exchange. The first ship class they can attack efficiently is Dreadnoughts, and that's only barely. Bigger ships are vastly more efficient, so don't waste your money on these.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Corvettes: Corvettes are extremely handy because they're extremely fast. I don't include Corvettes in battle fleets, personally. They can be used as meat with the same efficiency as bombers, but they're too useful in their other applications to waste them as meat when you don't have to. I keep Corvette fleets of 500 or so at jumpgates for recycler hunting and/or reinforcement of damaged fleets that are almost out of fighters. They're fast enough to make excellent raiders, and that speed also makes them great to use as emergency meat. Fighters are twice as efficient, but if you don't have enough and you've got a fleet that's about to get hit, get your Corvettes there instead.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Recyclers (RCs): These are not combat units, but that doesn't mean you don't need them. You need a ton. Resource denial is key to waging war. You should probably have at least 1000 for effective hit-and-run tactics. This will be covered in another volume.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Destroyers (DDs, tin cans): This is your first Plasma unit. Since the bulk of your fleet should be Plasma units, your Plasma research should be high, making Destroyers even more handy. They can be used as a combination attack/meat ship in attack fleets, but their low survivability makes them poor units to include in fleets that will spend much time in enemy territory. A few fighter waves can wipe them out very efficiently if you're caught while you're not online. Destroyers are the best ship for efficiently killing Cruisers, but the fact that Destroyers are unshielded means they're vulnerable to meat ships. If you find some naked Cruisers, wipe them out with Destroyers. I like to keep a fairly large Destroyer unit on standby at my jumpgates to facilitate rapid reinforcement of my bases if I see an enemy fleet coming. Destroyers pack a punch sufficient to damage Cruisers and HCs, which are primary fleet units. When you have Command Centers behind them, they play hell with enemy ratios, therefore creating larger debris piles over your planets. Handy! They're also fast enough for some Recycler hunting.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Frigates: These ships are handy for one thing: telling whether or not a player is an idiot mouthbreather. If he's got a lot of Frigates, chances are you're dealing with a noob. ATTENTION: FRIGATES SUCK. DON'T BUILD THEM. EVER.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Ion Frigates: Just like Frigates, only with Ion weapons and one point of shielding to go with a price tag 50%25 higher than it's counterpart. Think that makes them better? Not really.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Carriers: All those fighters don't do much good without a way to get them around. That's what these are for. They have less survivability than Fleet Carriers, but they're also faster. I keep a group at my jumpgates for rapid reinforcement. ALWAYS RETREAT YOUR CARRIERS BEFORE ATTACKING. If I see you attacking with Carriers, I'm going to hit you in the brainpan with a salmon. You have been warned.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Cruisers: This is the most efficient capital ship in the game. Build lots and lots of them. At least 35%25 of my total fleet strength is Cruisers. (Fighters are another 35%25 or so.) Cruisers are the most efficient ship for taking out anything up to Dreadnoughts (although Heavy Cruisers are more efficient against Dreadnoughts if they have fighters accompanying them). Cruisers are also the most efficient way to take out Planetary Rings, but it takes a whole lot of them. Make sure you have enough. Cruisers should be the backbone of your main battle fleets.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Heavy Cruisers (HCs): The only thing HCs can't hurt is a Death Star. HCs are handy against the big stuff, but I don't use them in main fleet formations unless I'm attacking something with BBs or higher. HCs are fairly efficient, but Cruisers will get you better ratios. HCs are great for taking out BBs and above, and as a bonus, they have enough shielding to be effectively immune to fighters, unless they have CCs behind them. HCs can be included in main battle fleets if you don't mind taking something of a ratio hit.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Battleships (BBs): The sad fact of AE is that the bigger the ships get, the less efficient they get. Every ship is vulnerable to smaller ships. That holds true for Battleships as well. The efficiency drop from HCs to BBs is huge. Most people have far too many. Still, Battleships have their uses. For taking out Levis and Death Stars, this is the most efficient ship. Battleships are also immune to fighters, making them a good ship for taking out weakly defended planets or for holding an occupation. Battleships are poor ships to include in most battle fleets due to their terrible inefficiency against Cruisers/HCs (which is what most enemy fleets are built around).%0a%3c %0a%3c :Fleet Carriers (FCs): FCs sacrifice speed for survivability. They have strong enough shields to shield-rape small units. If you have a calculator and you are very careful, it's possible to include FCs in attacks to improve ratios. This is dangerous, though. Don't do it if you're not experienced. You should have lots of FCs to move all your fighters around.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Dreadnoughts (DNs): The bigger you get, the less efficient you get. The big stuff is best used against things that can't hurt it. The strength of these units is their shields. They're great for taking out bases that have defenses weaker than Disruptors, so long as there aren't fleet units big enough to have a chance at taking you down. Dreadnoughts can make a fair addition to a combat fleet if A) you're fighting things that won't be able to kill one, given the dispersion of damage amongst your units and B) you're prepared to slow your entire fleet down in order to include them. If you might lose one, you're better off leaving it out. If you can safely add one without losing it, feel free; it'll soak some damage away from your other units.%0a%3c %0a%3c :Titans: This is the first unit with high enough shields to shield-rape Cruisers. That makes them very handy. On the downside, these things are slower than zombies playing Monopoly. Seriously, slooooooooooooow. HCs will kill them efficiently if you hit them with enough. BBs will kill them less efficiently, but require less bulk. Something like 130 HCs will kill a Titan, tech dependent, but it only takes about 20 BBs. The HCs should get about a 2:1 ratio, while the BBs will get less than 1.5:1. Titans are great to send out solo to smash bases with less than rings.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Before you start pillaging and burning you must learn somethings about your weapons and its usage.%0a> %0a> %0a> Not all ships are made equal!%0a> %0a> One of the problems with balanced fleet doctrine is that it tends to make people think they need to use ships that they have no need for in a fleet, giving their enemies an opportunity to destroy them more efficiently. Balance is good, yes, but that does mean you should be building frigates and including them in your fleets to disperse the damage. Let's take a look at all of your units and their applications. While some units are better than others, most have something they do well.%0a> %0a> %0a> Fighters: These are the staple of all fleets in AE-- defense, offense, everything. Fighters are the single most efficient ship in the game. The damage they absorb per credit is unparalleled. That makes fighters your #1 unit for use as cannon fodder. When we say you can never have too many fighters, we're being quite literal. A fleet that runs out of fighters will take far higher losses, and can be defeated in detail for obscene exchange rates by anyone who manages to catch them. Build thousands for base defense, and then keep building them for use with offensive fleets. You go through fighters at an obscene rate because fighters are basically designed to die. Application of fighter waves in combat can totally change your exchange rate for the better.%0a> %0a> Bombers: Same armor as fighters with twice the firepower and twice the cost. These are less efficient, but still make for pretty efficient meat. Their ability to harm cruisers makes them especially handy. Don't go overboard with Bombers, but they make a good addition to any fleet that needs to absorb a lot of damage, or one that's hitting a large group of cruisers. Since most people use a lot of cruisers, bombers can be very useful.%0a> %0a> Heavy Bombers (HBs): Heavy Bombers pack enough punch to take out main fleet units-- Cruisers and Heavy Cruisers-- but they're vulnerable and expensive, as well. Heavy Bombers are best used in waves after you have used fighter waves to destroy the enemy's unshielded units. Heavy Bombers are inefficient against unshielded units, and therefore should not be used in main fleet engagements. Enemy fighters will cut them to ribbons. HBs are also the best ships for breaking occupations if you have a proper amount of Command Centers.%0a> %0a> Ion Bombers (IBs): Double the price of Heavy Bombers, with the same power and armor. All they gain is one point of shielding, which does practically nothing for their survivability, and their weapons become Ion based, so 50%25 penetrates shielding. Oh, yay. These things suck. They're so expensive that they're not even efficient in waves. If you send a wave of Ion Bombers against capital ships of equal value-- be they cruisers, HCs, or BBs-- it's impossible for the Ion Bombers to come out ahead in the exchange. The first ship class they can attack efficiently is Dreadnoughts, and that's only barely. Bigger ships are vastly more efficient, so don't waste your money on these.%0a> %0a> Corvettes: Corvettes are extremely handy because they're extremely fast. I don't include Corvettes in battle fleets, personally. They can be used as meat with the same efficiency as bombers, but they're too useful in their other applications to waste them as meat when you don't have to. I keep Corvette fleets of 500 or so at jumpgates for recycler hunting and/or reinforcement of damaged fleets that are almost out of fighters. They're fast enough to make excellent raiders, and that speed also makes them great to use as emergency meat. Fighters are twice as efficient, but if you don't have enough and you've got a fleet that's about to get hit, get your Corvettes there instead.%0a> %0a> Recyclers (RCs): These are not combat units, but that doesn't mean you don't need them. You need a ton. Resource denial is key to waging war. You should probably have at least 1000 for effective hit-and-run tactics. This will be covered in another volume.%0a> %0a> Destroyers (DDs, tin cans): This is your first Plasma unit. Since the bulk of your fleet should be Plasma units, your Plasma research should be high, making Destroyers even more handy. They can be used as a combination attack/meat ship in attack fleets, but their low survivability makes them poor units to include in fleets that will spend much time in enemy territory. A few fighter waves can wipe them out very efficiently if you're caught while you're not online. Destroyers are the best ship for efficiently killing Cruisers, but the fact that Destroyers are unshielded means they're vulnerable to meat ships. If you find some naked Cruisers, wipe them out with Destroyers. I like to keep a fairly large Destroyer unit on standby at my jumpgates to facilitate rapid reinforcement of my bases if I see an enemy fleet coming. Destroyers pack a punch sufficient to damage Cruisers and HCs, which are primary fleet units. When you have Command Centers behind them, they play hell with enemy ratios, therefore creating larger debris piles over your planets. Handy! They're also fast enough for some Recycler hunting.%0a> %0a> Frigates: These ships are handy for one thing: telling whether or not a player is an idiot mouthbreather. If he's got a lot of Frigates, chances are you're dealing with a noob. ATTENTION: FRIGATES SUCK. DON'T BUILD THEM. EVER.%0a> %0a> Ion Frigates: Just like Frigates, only with Ion weapons and one point of shielding to go with a price tag 50%25 higher than it's counterpart. Think that makes them better? Not really.%0a> %0a> Carriers: All those fighters don't do much good without a way to get them around. That's what these are for. They have less survivability than Fleet Carriers, but they're also faster. I keep a group at my jumpgates for rapid reinforcement. ALWAYS RETREAT YOUR CARRIERS BEFORE ATTACKING. If I see you attacking with Carriers, I'm going to hit you in the brainpan with a salmon. You have been warned.%0a> %0a> Cruisers: This is the most efficient capital ship in the game. Build lots and lots of them. At least 35%25 of my total fleet strength is Cruisers. (Fighters are another 35%25 or so.) Cruisers are the most efficient ship for taking out anything up to Dreadnoughts (although Heavy Cruisers are more efficient against Dreadnoughts if they have fighters accompanying them). Cruisers are also the most efficient way to take out Planetary Rings, but it takes a whole lot of them. Make sure you have enough. Cruisers should be the backbone of your main battle fleets.%0a> %0a> Heavy Cruisers (HCs): The only thing HCs can't hurt is a Death Star. HCs are handy against the big stuff, but I don't use them in main fleet formations unless I'm attacking something with BBs or higher. HCs are fairly efficient, but Cruisers will get you better ratios. HCs are great for taking out BBs and above, and as a bonus, they have enough shielding to be effectively immune to fighters, unless they have CCs behind them. HCs can be included in main battle fleets if you don't mind taking something of a ratio hit.%0a> %0a> Battleships (BBs): The sad fact of AE is that the bigger the ships get, the less efficient they get. Every ship is vulnerable to smaller ships. That holds true for Battleships as well. The efficiency drop from HCs to BBs is huge. Most people have far too many. Still, Battleships have their uses. For taking out Levis and Death Stars, this is the most efficient ship. Battleships are also immune to fighters, making them a good ship for taking out weakly defended planets or for holding an occupation. Battleships are poor ships to include in most battle fleets due to their terrible inefficiency against Cruisers/HCs (which is what most enemy fleets are built around).%0a> %0a> Fleet Carriers (FCs): FCs sacrifice speed for survivability. They have strong enough shields to shield-rape small units. If you have a calculator and you are very careful, it's possible to include FCs in attacks to improve ratios. This is dangerous, though. Don't do it if you're not experienced. You should have lots of FCs to move all your fighters around.%0a> %0a> Dreadnoughts (DNs): The bigger you get, the less efficient you get. The big stuff is best used against things that can't hurt it. The strength of these units is their shields. They're great for taking out bases that have defenses weaker than Disruptors, so long as there aren't fleet units big enough to have a chance at taking you down. Dreadnoughts can make a fair addition to a combat fleet if A) you're fighting things that won't be able to kill one, given the dispersion of damage amongst your units and B) you're prepared to slow your entire fleet down in order to include them. If you might lose one, you're better off leaving it out. If you can safely add one without losing it, feel free; it'll soak some damage away from your other units.%0a> %0a> Titans: This is the first unit with high enough shields to shield-rape Cruisers. That makes them very handy. On the downside, these things are slower than zombies playing Monopoly. Seriously, slooooooooooooow. HCs will kill them efficiently if you hit them with enough. BBs will kill them less efficiently, but require less bulk. Something like 130 HCs will kill a Titan, tech dependent, but it only takes about 20 BBs. The HCs should get about a 2:1 ratio, while the BBs will get less than 1.5:1. Titans are great to send out solo to smash bases with less than rings.%0a> %0a57,61c49,53%0a%3c * Fighters and Cruisers should be the bulk of your fleet.%0a%3c * Keep enough HCs around to deal with the big stuff, with more than that if you want to use them in main fleets.%0a%3c * Don't build Frigates, Ion Frigates, or Ion Bombers unless you're sustained serious head injuries and you tend to drool a lot.%0a%3c * Bigger isn't always better. The bigger you get, the less efficient you get. Don't build too much of the big stuff.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Fighters and Cruisers should be the bulk of your fleet.%0a> Keep enough HCs around to deal with the big stuff, with more than that if you want to use them in main fleets.%0a> Don't build Frigates, Ion Frigates, or Ion Bombers unless you're sustained serious head injuries and you tend to drool a lot.%0a> Bigger isn't always better. The bigger you get, the less efficient you get. Don't build too much of the big stuff.%0a> %0a64,66c56,61%0a%3c Fleet Doctrine%0a%3c ==============%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a> %0a> %0a> PART 2%0a> %0a> %0a69,70c64,65%0a%3c '''Efficiency Doctrine.''' Efficiency Doctrine is basically just balanced doctrine evolved. Under balanced doctrine, you should have equal armor values of different units. That's all well and good, but against a thinking opponent, your fleets can be dismantled easily. The problem with balanced doctrine is that it frequently leads people to build less efficient ship types to mix into their fleets to soak damage from other types of ships. Against someone fighting efficiently, you're going to get owned.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Efficiency doctrine is basically just balanced doctrine evolved. Under balanced doctrine, you should have equal armor values of different units. That's all well and good, but against a thinking opponent, your fleets can be dismantled easily. The problem with balanced doctrine is that it frequently leads people to build less efficient ship types to mix into their fleets to soak damage from other types of ships. Against someone fighting efficiently, you're going to get owned.%0a> %0a72,73c67%0a%3c ----------------------------%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a76d69%0a%3c [@%0a86,87c79%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a89d80%0a%3c %0a92d82%0a%3c [@%0a95,96c85%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a99d87%0a%3c [@%0a113,114c101%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a117d103%0a%3c [@%0a122,123c108%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a126d110%0a%3c [@%0a146,147c130%0a%3c @]%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a150,153c133,134%0a%3c This is the problem with balanced doctrine. If you use a lot of%0a%3c different unit types, it does in fact disperse the damage across them.%0a%3c The problem is, any ''unshielded unit is vulnerable to fighters'', which are the most efficient unit in the game. Use a battle calculator to find how many fighters you need to attack with in one wave to destroy all the unshielded units. Drop that many and no more; overkill just wastes fighters and ruins your ratios as the enemy's shielded units kill the extra fighters with practically no losses. Once the enemy's unshielded units are gone, you send in the Cruisers---which are the most efficient ship to kill the shielded units---with the remaining fighters as a meatshield. By using only your most efficient units, you come out well ahead in the exchange.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> This is the problem with balanced doctrine. If you use a lot of different unit types, it does in fact disperse the damage across them. The problem is, any unshielded unit is vulnerable to fighters, which are the most efficient unit in the game. Use a battle calculator to find how many fighters you need to attack with in one wave to destroy all the unshielded units. Drop that many and no more; overkill just wastes fighters and ruins your ratios as the enemy's shielded units kill the extra fighters with practically no losses. Once the enemy's unshielded units are gone, you send in the Cruisers-- which are the most efficient ship to kill the shielded units-- with the remaining fighters as a meatshield. By using only your most efficient units, you come out well ahead in the exchange.%0a> %0a159,160c140%0a%3c --------------%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a170a151,153%0a> %0a> %0a> %0a176,177c159%0a%3c ==================%0a%3c %0a---%0a> %0a180,181c162,163%0a%3c Well, it's an idea. Granted, it's one that goes against thousands of years of military strategy. It may look good on paper, but the fact is initiative is too valuable an asset in war. If you sit back and wait for your enemy to come to you, he will. And he'll do it with overwhelming force. You'll get good exchange rates, and then your enemy will scoop all the debris and turn it into fleet to replace his losses. Meanwhile, all your fleet was at home where it just got smashed, so you have no hope of liberating your bases. Because your enemy was under no pressure, he could amass a force to come after you at his leisure. It's the same reason hackers are always one step ahead of security: It's impossible to create an impregnable defense. If you have a determined enemy who knows what he's dealing with---all he has to do is sit a scout somewhere in the region to watch you---then he can figure out exactly what he needs to break your defenses. Given time, he'll put together a fleet to break you, and he doesn't have to worry about uncovering one of his systems to do it because he's not under any pressure.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Well, it's an idea. Granted, it's one that goes against thousands of years of military strategy. It may look good on paper, but the fact is initiative is too valuable an asset in war. If you sit back and wait for your enemy to come to you, he will. And he'll do it with overwhelming force. You'll get good exchange rates, and then your enemy will scoop all the debris and turn it into fleet to replace his losses. Meanwhile, all your fleet was at home where it just got smashed, so you have no hope of liberating your bases. Because your enemy was under no pressure, he could amass a force to come after you at his leisure. It's the same reason hackers are always one step ahead of security: It's impossible to create an impregnable defense. If you have a determined enemy who knows what he's dealing with-- all he has to do is sit a scout somewhere in the region to watch you-- then he can figure out exactly what he needs to break your defenses. Given time, he'll put together a fleet to break you, and he doesn't have to worry about uncovering one of his systems to do it because he's not under any pressure.%0a> %0a190,191c172,173%0a%3c It's fairly simple: First one to show aggression rides the rapetrain. It doesn't matter how well-defended he is. It doesn't matter if there are softer targets around. The soft targets don't pose a threat. Not only have they shown no aggression, but they're also easy meat for whenever you get around to them. Focus on the enemy aggressors, and knock them back on their heels. Pick one of their production bases---as a bonus, these are frequently jumpgate worlds, and often house a large fleet if it's not out on assault duty---and smash it. These are usually well defended worlds, and you will take significant losses in order to break them. If you don't have enough fleet to take it without being crippled, coordinate with guildmates. Don't break yourself to send a message, but if you don't have enough fleet to take one base without breaking yourself, you really aren't ready for war yet to begin with.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> It's fairly simple: First one to show aggression rides the rapetrain. It doesn't matter how well-defended he is. It doesn't matter if there are softer targets around. The soft targets don't pose a threat. Not only have they shown no aggression, but they're also easy meat for whenever you get around to them. Focus on the enemy aggressors, and knock them back on their heels. Pick one of their production bases-- as a bonus, these are frequently jumpgate worlds, and often house a large fleet if it's not out on assault duty-- and smash it. These are usually well defended worlds, and you will take significant losses in order to break them. If you don't have enough fleet to take it without being crippled, coordinate with guildmates. Don't break yourself to send a message, but if you don't have enough fleet to take one base without breaking yourself, you really aren't ready for war yet to begin with.%0a> %0a222,223c204,205%0a%3c The ideal way to keep a fleet functioning is to keep it in supply. Fleet Carriers are essential in combat fleets, with their high survivability saving you tons of credits if you get caught flat-footed. They make poor resupply vessels, though, because they're not as fast. Regular carriers are far easier to kill, but are also 33%25 faster than Fleet Carriers. This makes them ideal as rear echelon units. They are never intended to see combat. The idea is to dispatch your resupply carriers from a jumpgate, drop off their fighter compliment for the FCs in the field to pick up, and then run them back home. In my opinion, Carriers should only be built for resupply purposes, or for when you need to get more fighter transport up fast. Fleet Carriers not only have higher survivability, but they also have more hangar space per credit spent than Carriers do---even if it's not by much. Carriers serve a very specific role once you get FCs, and this is it. Keep plenty of fighters at the jumpgate where the carriers are on standby, and trying to keep enough bombers and heavy bombers on hand to fill your carriers for those instances when your enemy is vulnerable to a bomber or HB drop. Focus on fighters, though.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> The ideal way to keep a fleet functioning is to keep it in supply. Fleet Carriers are essential in combat fleets, with their high survivability saving you tons of credits if you get caught flat-footed. They make poor resupply vessels, though, because they're not as fast. Regular carriers are far easier to kill, but are also 33%25 faster than Fleet Carriers. This makes them ideal as rear echelon units. They are never intended to see combat. The idea is to dispatch your resupply carriers from a jumpgate, drop off their fighter compliment for the FCs in the field to pick up, and then run them back home. In my opinion, Carriers should only be built for resupply purposes, or for when you need to get more fighter transport up fast. Fleet Carriers not only have higher survivability, but they also have more hangar space per credit spent than Carriers do-- even if it's not by much. Carriers serve a very specific role once you get FCs, and this is it. Keep plenty of fighters at the jumpgate where the carriers are on standby, and trying to keep enough bombers and heavy bombers on hand to fill your carriers for those instances when your enemy is vulnerable to a bomber or HB drop. 